Note:
R Emitter - Buffered output for R code generation

This file provides buffered output functionality for R code generation.
Handles automatic buffer growth, string emission, and indentation following
R conventions.

Features:
- Dynamic buffer growth (doubles when full)
- Efficient string and character emission
- Indentation support (2 spaces for R convention)
- Memory-safe buffer management
- Null-terminated output strings

R Code Style Conventions:
- Indentation: 2 spaces (R style guide standard)
- No semicolons required (newlines separate statements)
- Spacing around operators: x <- 1 + 2
- Assignment: Prefer <- over =
- Function calls: No space before parentheses (foo(x))
- Comments: # for single-line comments only

Dependencies:
- compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa
:End Note

Import "../emitter_common.runa" as EmitterCommon

Note: ============================================================================
Note: R Emitter Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Mirrors the layout expected by emitter_common (buffer pointer, capacity, length).
A struct rather than three globals so multiple emitters can coexist (e.g., main
output + speculative buffer for backtracking during code lowering).
@End Reasoning
Type called "REmitter":
    buffer as Integer           Note: Output buffer
    capacity as Integer         Note: Buffer capacity
    length as Integer           Note: Current length (bytes used)
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Emitter Creation and Destruction
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Thin wrapper that delegates to the shared emitter_common allocator so all
language backends share the same growth strategy and ownership rules.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_r_emitter" returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_create from EmitterCommon
End Process

@Reasoning:
Releases both the inner byte buffer and the emitter struct itself via the
shared destructor so backends cannot leak buffers by forgetting cleanup.
@End Reasoning
Process called "destroy_r_emitter" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_destroy from EmitterCommon with emitter
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Buffer Management
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Bounded growth guard against runaway allocations during large translation
units; emitter_common doubles the buffer when needed is greater than the
remaining tail, keeping amortised O(1) append cost.
@End Reasoning
Process called "ensure_capacity" takes emitter as Integer, needed as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_ensure_capacity from EmitterCommon with emitter, needed
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Output Functions
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Single-byte append is the hot path for keyword/punctuation emission; delegating
to emitter_common keeps the inlining boundary at one cross-module call site.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_char" takes emitter as Integer, char as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, char
End Process

@Reasoning:
Walks str until the NUL terminator and appends each byte; assumes str is a
C-style null-terminated string produced by the lowering pass.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_string" takes emitter as Integer, str as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_emit_string from EmitterCommon with emitter, str
End Process

@Reasoning:
Convenience for statement emission where every line in R ends with a newline
rather than a semicolon; centralises the newline byte (10) so platform line
endings stay consistent across the backend.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_line" takes emitter as Integer, str as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit string followed by newline

    proc emit_string with emitter, str
    proc emit_char with emitter, 10  Note: newline

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
R statements terminate on newline rather than semicolon, so emitters must
emit explicit newlines to separate assignments and function calls.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_newline" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit newline character

    proc emit_char with emitter, 10  Note: newline

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single-space helper used between operators and operands to satisfy the
Tidyverse style guide which mandates surrounding spaces on binary operators.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_space" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit single space character

    proc emit_char with emitter, 32  Note: space

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
R conventionally uses 2 spaces for indentation. This follows the Tidyverse
style guide and is the R community standard, multiplied by nesting depth.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_indent" takes emitter as Integer, level as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit indentation (2 spaces per level for R convention)

    @Reasoning:
    R conventionally uses 2 spaces for indentation. This follows
    the Tidyverse style guide and is the R community standard.
    @End Reasoning

    Let total_spaces be level multiplied by 2
    Let count be 0

    While count is less than total_spaces:
        proc emit_char with emitter, 32  Note: space
        Set count to count plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: R-Specific Output Functions
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
R style guide recommends spaces around binary operators (e.g., "x <- 1 + 2"
not "x<-1+2"). Centralising the spacing rule here keeps every operator
emission consistent without scattering space literals through call sites.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_operator" takes emitter as Integer, op as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit operator with proper spacing

    @Reasoning:
    R style guide recommends spaces around binary operators
    (e.g., "x <- 1 + 2" not "x<-1+2"). This ensures readable,
    idiomatic R code output.
    @End Reasoning

    proc emit_space with emitter
    proc emit_string with emitter, op
    proc emit_space with emitter

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
R has three assignment operators (<-, =, ->) but <- is preferred by the
style guide for clarity and avoids ambiguity with named-argument equality
inside function calls.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_assignment" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit R assignment operator (<-)

    @Reasoning:
    R has multiple assignment operators, but <- is preferred
    in the style guide over = for clarity and tradition.
    @End Reasoning

    proc emit_string with emitter, " <- "

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
R 4.1+ ships a native pipe operator |> that is faster than the magrittr
%>% because it is a syntactic transformation rather than a function call;
this is the default for newly-generated code.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_pipe" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit R pipe operator (|>)

    @Reasoning:
    R 4.1+ has native pipe operator |>. We prefer this over
    %>% (magrittr) for compatibility and performance.
    @End Reasoning

    proc emit_string with emitter, " |> "

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Fallback pipe for pre-4.1 R installations or generated code that must run
on older R versions; magrittr is universally available via tidyverse.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_magrittr_pipe" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit magrittr pipe operator (%>%)

    proc emit_string with emitter, " %>% "

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
R only supports single-line # comments. Multi-line commentary must be
emitted as multiple # lines by the caller; this helper handles only one
comment line so the caller controls newline placement.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_comment" takes emitter as Integer, text as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit R comment

    @Reasoning:
    R only supports single-line comments with #. Multi-line
    comments require multiple # lines.
    @End Reasoning

    proc emit_string with emitter, "# "
    proc emit_string with emitter, text

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
The tilde forms R's formula objects (lm(y ~ x)); kept as its own emitter
because formulas are first-class objects, not just syntactic operators.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_formula" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit formula operator (~)

    proc emit_string with emitter, " ~ "

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
R distinguishes exported (::) from internal (:::) symbol access; this
helper centralises that decision so callers pass a single flag rather than
hand-coding the operator difference.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_namespace" takes emitter as Integer, is_internal as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit namespace accessor (:: or :::)

    If is_internal is equal to 1:
        proc emit_string with emitter, ":::"
    Otherwise:
        proc emit_string with emitter, "::"
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
The $ operator is R's primary way to access named elements of lists,
data frames, and environments; distinct from @ which accesses S4 slots.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_member_access" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit member access operator ($)

    proc emit_string with emitter, "$"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
The @ operator accesses S4 class slots and is strictly separate from $;
emitting it through a dedicated helper prevents collision with the
annotation-block @ sigil at the source level.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_slot_access" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit slot access operator (@)

    proc emit_string with emitter, "@"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Keyword constant - factored into its own emitter so any future spelling
change (e.g. style-guide-driven case shift) happens in exactly one place.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_function_keyword" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit function keyword

    proc emit_string with emitter, "function"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
R 4.1+ supports lambda syntax \(x) x + 1 as shorthand for function(x).
Backslash must be escaped here as "\\" in the Runa string literal.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_lambda_start" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit lambda start (\)

    @Reasoning:
    R 4.1+ supports lambda syntax: \(x) x + 1
    This is shorthand for function(x) x + 1
    @End Reasoning

    proc emit_string with emitter, "\\"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Conditional keyword - kept as a dedicated emitter so the control-flow
lowering pass calls emit_if_keyword rather than spelling the literal,
preserving a single point of change.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_if_keyword" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit if keyword

    proc emit_string with emitter, "if"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
R uses "else" (not "elseif" or "elif") and it must appear on the same line
as the closing brace of the if-block; this helper emits only the bare
keyword so callers control the surrounding whitespace.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_else_keyword" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit else keyword

    proc emit_string with emitter, "else"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Loop keyword paired with a (condition) - kept symmetrical with emit_for_keyword
and emit_repeat_keyword so the loop lowering pass selects by HIR node kind.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_while_keyword" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit while keyword

    proc emit_string with emitter, "while"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
R for-loops require an "in" clause (for (x in xs)); see emit_in_keyword
for the companion. Kept as a dedicated emitter for HIR loop dispatch.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_for_keyword" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit for keyword

    proc emit_string with emitter, "for"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
R's repeat loop has no condition (use break to exit); emitted distinctly
because HIR may lower do-while patterns to repeat + conditional break.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_repeat_keyword" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit repeat keyword

    proc emit_string with emitter, "repeat"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
The "in" particle appears in for (x in xs) but R reuses it nowhere else,
unlike Python; isolating it prevents accidental misuse in other contexts.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_in_keyword" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit in keyword

    proc emit_string with emitter, "in"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
R's break exits the innermost loop only; emitted by the HIR lowering pass
when a break_statement is encountered.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_break_keyword" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit break keyword

    proc emit_string with emitter, "break"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
R uses "next" where most languages use "continue"; kept as a distinct
emitter so the HIR continue_statement maps cleanly to the R idiom.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_next_keyword" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit next keyword (R's continue)

    proc emit_string with emitter, "next"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
R's return() is a function, not a keyword, but stylistically callers omit
the parentheses for keyword-like usage; this helper emits the bare word.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_return_keyword" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit return keyword

    proc emit_string with emitter, "return"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
R booleans are uppercase TRUE/FALSE (with single-letter aliases T/F that
can be reassigned and are therefore unsafe); we emit the canonical form.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_true" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit TRUE literal

    proc emit_string with emitter, "TRUE"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
R booleans are uppercase TRUE/FALSE; T/F are aliases but can be rebound,
so we always emit the canonical FALSE for safety against override attacks.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_false" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit FALSE literal

    proc emit_string with emitter, "FALSE"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
R distinguishes NULL (empty/missing value) from NA (statistical missing);
the lowering pass must pick the right literal based on the source semantic.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_null" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit NULL literal

    proc emit_string with emitter, "NULL"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
NA is R's typed missing-value marker (NA_integer_, NA_real_, etc.) and is
semantically distinct from NULL; emitted only where statistical missing
applies, not for ordinary nullable references.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_na" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit NA literal

    proc emit_string with emitter, "NA"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
IEEE-754 NaN literal; distinct from NA because most R operations propagate
NaN through arithmetic but treat NA as a separate missing-data marker.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_nan" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit NaN literal

    proc emit_string with emitter, "NaN"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Positive infinity literal; negation must be emitted by the caller as "-Inf"
because the lexer parses leading minus as a unary operator, not part of
the literal.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_inf" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit Inf literal

    proc emit_string with emitter, "Inf"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Function-call and expression-grouping delimiter; emitted by every call-site
lowering and around conditional expressions. Symmetric with emit_right_paren.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_left_paren" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit left parenthesis

    proc emit_string with emitter, "("

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Closes function calls and grouping; the lowering pass must track paired
depth in HIR to balance emission.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_right_paren" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit right parenthesis

    proc emit_string with emitter, ")"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
R block delimiter; required for multi-statement bodies but optional for
single-statement if/while bodies. The lowering pass always emits braces
for clarity and to avoid the dangling-else ambiguity.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_left_brace" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit left brace

    proc emit_string with emitter, "{"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Closes a block; paired with emit_left_brace by depth tracking in the
caller, never balanced inside this emitter.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_right_brace" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit right brace

    proc emit_string with emitter, "}"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single-bracket indexing in R preserves type (x[1] on a list returns a list);
distinct semantics from [[ ]] (see emit_double_left_bracket) which extracts
the element directly.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_left_bracket" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit left bracket

    proc emit_string with emitter, "["

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Closes a single-bracket index expression; semantic partner of emit_left_bracket.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_right_bracket" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit right bracket

    proc emit_string with emitter, "]"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
[[ ]] performs element extraction (unwrapping) on lists rather than the
list-preserving single-bracket subset; HIR list-element-access lowers here.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_double_left_bracket" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit double left bracket

    proc emit_string with emitter, "[["

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Closes a double-bracket extraction. Two right brackets must be emitted as
a single token "]]" to avoid ambiguity with x[[1]][1].
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_double_right_bracket" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit double right bracket

    proc emit_string with emitter, "]]"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bare-comma separator; the spaced form (emit_comma_space) is preferred per
style guide but bare-comma is needed inside subscripts like x[,1].
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_comma" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit comma

    proc emit_string with emitter, ","

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Style-guide-compliant argument separator with trailing space; preferred
for function calls and constructor argument lists.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_comma_space" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit comma followed by space

    proc emit_string with emitter, ", "

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
R accepts semicolons as alternative statement terminators but they are
rarely used; emitted only when the source explicitly used semicolon to
preserve formatting intent during translation.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_semicolon" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit semicolon (rarely used in R)

    proc emit_string with emitter, ";"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
The colon in R is the integer-sequence operator (1:10) and is the most
efficient way to generate dense integer ranges, faster than seq().
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_colon" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit colon (sequence operator)

    proc emit_string with emitter, ":"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
c() is R's universal vector constructor; lowered from HIR array literals.
A separate emitter keeps the name centralised in case future versions
prefer base::c() qualification.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_vector_function" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit c (vector creation function)

    proc emit_string with emitter, "c"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
list() constructs R's heterogeneous container, in contrast to c() which
coerces to a single type; HIR heterogeneous-record/tuple lowering emits this.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_list_function" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit list function

    proc emit_string with emitter, "list"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
R variadic parameter; passed through to inner functions with ..n indexing.
Distinct from a literal three-dot identifier because R lexes ... atomically.
@End Reasoning
Process called "emit_varargs" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Emit ... (varargs)

    proc emit_string with emitter, "..."

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Output Retrieval
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Returns the inner buffer pointer; the caller must NUL-terminate or use the
length from get_length because emitter_common does not append a trailing NUL.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_output" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_get_output from EmitterCommon with emitter
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns bytes written so far so callers can stream the buffer (e.g., write
to file in chunks) without scanning for NUL.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_length" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_length from EmitterCommon with emitter
End Process

@Reasoning:
Rewinds the write pointer to zero without freeing the buffer, allowing the
emitter to be reused for the next translation unit; amortises allocation cost.
@End Reasoning
Process called "reset" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_reset from EmitterCommon with emitter
End Process

@Reasoning:
Alias for reset() preserved because some HIR test harnesses call clear();
delegates rather than duplicating the buffer-rewind logic.
@End Reasoning
Process called "clear" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Clear emitter (alias for reset)

    Return proc reset with emitter
End Process
